A common scenario that I have come across in projects, as well as having seen others work around, has been dealing with identifying whether a set has duplicates as well as getting the duplicate values/counts. 

I've written extensions for projects that utilize the optimized Set<TElement> internal class that does a fast-return when the first duplicate object is hit for HasDuplicates(), as well as adding an int object to the to the Slot<TElement> internal class that handles the number of times the object has been added/attempted to be added to the Set. 

This would improve performance over the most common way I have seen developers do this:

**HasDuplicates**
Current workaround: 
``` cs
public static bool HasDuplicates<TSource>(IEnumerable<TSource> source, IEqualityComparer<TSource> comparer){
    return source.Count() == source.Distinct(comparer).Count();
}
```

Optimized method (using Set<TSource>):
``` cs 
public static bool HasDuplicates<TSource>(IEnumerable<TSource> source, IEqualityComparer<TSource> comparer){
    var set = new Set<TSource>(comparer);
    foreach (var element in source)
    {
        if (!set.Add(element))
        {
            return true;
        }
     }
     return false;
}
```


**Duplicates**
Current workaround:
``` cs 
public static IEnumerable<KeyValuePair<TSource, int>> Duplicates<TSource>(this IEnumerable<TSource> source, IEqualityComparer<TSource> comparer){
    return source.GroupBy(element => element).Select(x =>
                new KeyValuePair<TSource, int>(x.Key, x.Count())).Where(x => x.Value > 1);
}
```

Optimized method (using modified Set<TSource> and Slot<TSource>):
``` cs
public static IEnumerable<KeyValuePair<TSource, int>> Duplicates<TSource>(this IEnumerable<TSource> source, IEqualityComparer<TSource> comparer){
    var set = new Set<TSource>(comparer);
    foreach(var element in source)
    {
        set.Add(element);
    }
    return set.ToEnumerableWithCount();
}
```
**New method to add to Set<TSource>**
``` cs
public IEnumerable<KeyValuePair<TElement,int>> ToEnumerableWithCount(){
    return _slots.Where(x => x._count > 1).Select(x =< new KeyValuePair<TElement, int>(x._value, x._count));
}
```

There would be a couple other changes that would be made to the Add & Remove methods on `Set<TSource>`, as well as adding the `internal int _count` property to `Slot<TSource>`.

Hello,

i'm working with .NET Core 2.2.3 and the previous versions since 2018 running it on a Linux ARM embedded device..

Today i ported my code handling network events from a windows project to the new linux project.
To detect changes on the network interface or availability i use `NetworkChange.NetworkAvailabilityChanged`

The attached event handler is called if i make changes on the interface using the `ip` utility so all is good. But if i unplugg the network cable there is no event.

I looked further into the corefx code to check how the event is being fired which is done by [src/Native/Unix/System.Native/pal_networkchange.c](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/master/src/Native/Unix/System.Native/pal_networkchange.c)

I then made a small command line program to test the code on my virtual machine and embedded device. So if i use the code without changes, there is a event on the virtual machine because of the message RTMNEW_ROUTE but not on the embedded device which does not report that message.

The interface itself is always enabled i only disconnect the ethernet cable.

It might be a problem by the following code which i think does not correctly check the `ifi_family` please correct my if i'm wrong.

```
static NetworkChangeKind ReadNewLinkMessage(struct nlmsghdr* hdr)
{
    assert(hdr != NULL);
    struct ifinfomsg* ifimsg;
    ifimsg = (struct ifinfomsg*)NLMSG_DATA(hdr);
    if (ifimsg->ifi_family == AF_INET)
    {
        if ((ifimsg->ifi_flags & IFF_UP) != 0)
        {
            return LinkAdded;
        }
    }

    return None;
}
```

According to the [RTNETLINK(7)](http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/rtnetlink.7.html) documentation The `ifi_family` is always `AF_UNSPEC` if i'm not wrong. My tests on the virtual machine and embedded device never showed a message with the `ifi_family` being not `0`.

Also the check for `IFF_UP` does only check if the interface itself e.g. eth0 is enabled/up which it was in my case. But that does not mean that the cable is plugged, which is reported by the flag `IFF_LOWER_UP` if present the cable is plugged in. So handling that flag could be an option.

So in my case that code always returns `None` which will not report any event to the managed part. Removing that comparison also does not report an event to the registered managed event handler because only LinkAdded is reported which is not handled by `OnSocketEvent` 

See [src/System.Net.NetworkInformation/src/System/Net/NetworkInformation/NetworkAddressChange.Linux.cs](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/master/src/System.Net.NetworkInformation/src/System/Net/NetworkInformation/NetworkAddressChange.Linux.cs)

Only the following three change kinds are handled in that method.

```
Interop.Sys.NetworkChangeKind.AddressAdded
Interop.Sys.NetworkChangeKind.AddressRemoved
Interop.Sys.NetworkChangeKind.AvailabilityChanged
```

Is this as designed? I think `Interop.Sys.NetworkChangeKind.AvailabilityChanged` should report if the physical link status of an interface changes or a separate event like `PhysicalStatusChanged` should be added.

What's the reason unsigned types were left out of `SequenceReader<T>`? CLS compliance? I couldn't find any details on it.

It would be really nice if it mirrored the API surface of `BinaryPrimitives` (or `Utf8Parser` for that matter).

I propose the following:

```diff
namespace System.Buffers
{
    public static partial class SequenceReaderExtensions
    {
        public static bool TryReadLittleEndian(ref this SequenceReader<byte> reader, out short value);
        public static bool TryReadBigEndian(ref this SequenceReader<byte> reader, out short value);

        public static bool TryReadLittleEndian(ref this SequenceReader<byte> reader, out int value);
        public static bool TryReadBigEndian(ref this SequenceReader<byte> reader, out int value);

        public static bool TryReadLittleEndian(ref this SequenceReader<byte> reader, out long value);
        public static bool TryReadBigEndian(ref this SequenceReader<byte> reader, out long value);

+       [CLSCompliant(false)]
+       public static bool TryReadLittleEndian(ref this SequenceReader<byte> reader, out ushort value);
+       [CLSCompliant(false)]
+       public static bool TryReadBigEndian(ref this SequenceReader<byte> reader, out ushort value);
+
+       [CLSCompliant(false)]
+       public static bool TryReadLittleEndian(ref this SequenceReader<byte> reader, out uint value);
+       [CLSCompliant(false)]
+       public static bool TryReadBigEndian(ref this SequenceReader<byte> reader, out uint value);
+
+       [CLSCompliant(false)]
+       public static bool TryReadLittleEndian(ref this SequenceReader<byte> reader, out ulong value);
+       [CLSCompliant(false)]
+       public static bool TryReadBigEndian(ref this SequenceReader<byte> reader, out ulong value);
    }
}
```

It would also be nice if it had non-`Try*` alternatives, but that could be left for a separate proposal.

